"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-tatjana-smith-aims-for-heyns-history-2024-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbTatjana Smith aims for unique HEYNS history at the 2024 Paris Olympics  The double is on the cards.  Tatjana Smith is gunning for a unique slice of South African swimming history at the Paris 2024 Olympics.  Smithstands to become only the second swimmer in history after Penny Heyns in 1996 to complete the 100m and 200m breaststroke golden double at the same Olympics event. She wasn't yet born when Heyns accomplished this historic feat. The 27-year-old contests her 200m breaststroke heat onWednesday 31 July at 11:00 SA time. Thesemi-finals go at 21:51 and 21:58.The finalis onThursday 01 August at 21:04.You know thatNando's will be watching. Smith won this event in Tokyo with a time of2.18.95, a world record which has since been eclipsed by Russian Evgeniia Chikunova in 2023 with a time of2.17.55.Will Smith take her record back?  Smith touched the wall first in1.05.28in the 100m breaststroke thanks to amassive surge in the final quarter of the race.China's Tang Qianting scooped silver and a visibly delighted Mona McSharry, from Ireland, got the bronze.  \\\"I had no idea where I was, literally most of the race,\\\" admitted Smith afterwards.  \\\"I actually did not think I medalled because when I turned to my left, the two blocks next to me both had lights on and it felt like someone else on the other side touched first.  \\\"So I actually did not think I was medalling.  \\\"My main goal was just to not do what I did in Tokyo and look around, so literally the last 15 metres, I was like, no, close your eyes, let us just go.\\\"  \\\"I swam for everyone that's been there for me, that's believed with me, for our country as well.\\\"  Tatjana is just the fifth South African to win an individual Olympic swimming title after Joan Harrison in 1952, Penny Heynes in 1996, Cameron van der Burgh in 2012 and Chad le Clos in 2012). She regards Heyns and Le Clos as sporting heroes, along with iconic Olympian pair Michael Phelps and Usain Bolt.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.com. You can also send a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1. Follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor your social fix.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 